{"key":"post-10794510","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10794510</id>\n<content>There's lots of nutrients for fungi in coir.&amp;nbsp; It's the equal of horse manure.&amp;nbsp; Fungi spores simply don't germinate well on it, but live mycelium eats it up.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I prefer layering.&amp;nbsp; It causes less damage to the spawn, and also the mycelium tends to recover faster and be more robust when layered over mixing.&amp;nbsp; It's important to make sure there's at least a thin layer of bulk substrate covering all the spawn.&amp;nbsp; Don't leave any grains exposed on the surface.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10794649</next>\n<prev>10794435</prev>\n<first>10790918</first>\n<last>10794842</last>\n<when>1249351327</when>\n<utime>08/04/09 05:02 AM</utime>\n</post>"}